 literary study of these important poems by studying the epigrams within the context of the poetry books in which they were originally collected. Drawing upon ancient sources as well as recent papyrological discoveries, Gutzwiller reconstructs the nature of Hellenistic epigram books and interprets individual poems as if they remained part of their original collections. This approach results in illuminating and original readings of many major poets, and demonstrates that individual epigrammatists were differentiated by gender, ethnicity, class status, and philosophical views. In an important final chapter, Gutzwiller reconstructs much of the poetic structure of Meleager's Garland, an ancient anthology of Hellenistic epigrams.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBooks and readingxMediterranean Region. 0aBooks and readingzMediterranean Region. 0aEpigrams, GreekxHistory and criticism. 0aGreek poetry, HellenisticxHistory and criticism. 0aLiterary form. 4aAncient Archaeology. 4aAncient History. 4aNear and Middle Eastern History. 4aclassical literature. 4aethics. 4agender. 4ahistory. 4aliterature. 4amilitary history. 4amoral philosophy. 4aphilosophy. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aancient greece.  aancient greek poetry.  aancient history.  aancient literature.  aancient poetry.  aclass status.  aclassical literature.  aepigram book.  aepigrammata.  aepigrams.  aerotic literature.  aethnicity.  agarland.  agender studies.  agreek poetry.  ahellenistic culture and society series.  ahellenistic period.  ahistory of books.  aliterary criticism.  aliterary study.  amanuscripts.  ameleager.  apapyrological.  aphilosophy.  aprivate readings.  apublic recitation.  asympotic literature.  athird century history.  athird cent